re (p = 0.056). Performance in all other cognitive tasks did not differ significantly between BRJ and PLA at any measurement point (p ≥ 0.141). Conclusion: This study suggests that BRJ improves physiological function and exercise performance, but not cognitive function, at simulated moderate and very-high altitude.},
author = {Shannon, Oliver M. and Duckworth, Lauren and Barlow, Matthew J. and Deighton, Kevin and Matu, Jamie and Williams, Emily L. and Woods, David and Xie, Long and Stephan, Blossom C.M. and Siervo, Mario and O'Hara, John P.},
doi = {10.3389/fphys.2017.00401},
